#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:18
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling ZFS and setting Up the pool"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "First, enter this command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "/sbin/modprobe zfs\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "This should not return an error, it should simply return to the command prompt when done. If you get an error, stop now and begin troubleshooting. Again, make sure that secure boot is off as that will be the most likely culprit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next we need to take a look at the disks on our system, determine what has the OS loaded on it, and what is available to use for the ZFS pool. We will do this with _lsblk_:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "lsblk\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "Which should return something like this (your system will be different!):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "AME   MAJ:MIN RM   SIZE RO TYPE MOUNTPOINT\n"
"loop0    7:0    0  32.3M  1 loop /var/lib/snapd/snap/snapd/11588\n"
"loop1    7:1    0  55.5M  1 loop /var/lib/snapd/snap/core18/1997\n"
"loop2    7:2    0  68.8M  1 loop /var/lib/snapd/snap/lxd/20037\n"
"sda      8:0    0 119.2G  0 disk\n"
"├─sda1   8:1    0   600M  0 part /boot/efi\n"
"├─sda2   8:2    0     1G  0 part /boot\n"
"├─sda3   8:3    0  11.9G  0 part [SWAP]\n"
"├─sda4   8:4    0     2G  0 part /home\n"
"└─sda5   8:5    0 103.7G  0 part /\n"
"sdb      8:16   0 119.2G  0 disk\n"
"├─sdb1   8:17   0 119.2G  0 part\n"
"└─sdb9   8:25   0     8M  0 part\n"
"sdc      8:32   0 149.1G  0 disk\n"
"└─sdc1   8:33   0 149.1G  0 part\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this listing, we can see that */dev/sda* is in use by the operating system, so we are going to use */dev/sdb* for our zpool. Note that if you have multiple free hard drives, you may wish to consider using raidz (a software raid specifically for ZFS).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "That falls outside the scope of this document, but should definitely be a consideration for production, as it offers better performance and redundancy. For now, let's create our pool on the single device we have identified:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "zpool create storage /dev/sdb\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "What this says is to create a pool called \"storage\" that is ZFS on the device */dev/sdb*.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/02-zfs_setup.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the pool is created, it's a good idea to reboot the server again at this point.\n"
msgstr ""

